## Mugwort — The Herb of Midsummer Dreaming

No herb appears more consistently in midsummer dream customs than mugwort (*Artemisia vulgaris*).

It was gathered specifically around St. John’s Eve across much of Europe because people believed the plant reached maximum strength at the solstice.

In Germany, Poland, the Balkans, Scandinavia, and the British Isles, mugwort was:

- woven into midsummer belts and crowns,
- thrown into bonfires,
- carried during night walks,
- placed beneath pillows for prophetic dreams,
- used by unmarried women seeking visions of future spouses.

Its role was not only visionary but protective.

Dreaming was never approached casually in folk tradition. Opening the road required guarding the dreamer as well.

Mugwort occupied both roles at once.

Unlike harsher Artemisia plants like wormwood, mugwort was considered steadying rather than aggressive. It allowed symbolic dreams to rise gradually instead of forcing visions through intensity.

This distinction mattered.

