## Flower Divination and the Language of Plants

Midsummer rites often blurred the line between dreaming and divination.

Flowers themselves became prophetic tools.

St. John’s wort, yarrow, mugwort, vervain, fern, chamomile, and wildflowers gathered at twilight were believed to carry unusual power on solstice night.

Some traditions judged omens by:

- which flowers wilted first,
- whether wreaths floated or sank,
- how herbs burned in the fire,
- which scents appeared strongest in dreams,
- what direction smoke traveled.

Plants gathered on midsummer night were often dried and kept all year for protection, fertility, healing, and dream-work.

The solstice did not simply bless the ritual.

It charged the plants themselves.

