## Bonfires and Ecstatic Liminality

Midsummer fires were not decorative celebrations.

They were ritual technologies.

People leapt through flames for purification, fertility, luck, and protection against illness or bad fortune. Livestock were driven between fires. Ashes were scattered into fields. Smoke passed over people, crops, and homes.

The fire altered consciousness collectively.

Songs, dancing, drinking, drumming, heat, sleeplessness, smoke, herbs, and prolonged light created an atmosphere modern life rarely experiences anymore.

Many midsummer dream traditions only make sense inside that altered environment.

People stayed awake until the edge of dawn, then slept briefly after ritual activity, herb smoke, emotional intensity, and sensory exhaustion.

Dreams following these nights were treated as especially charged because the dreamer had already crossed a threshold before sleep even began.

