## Midsummer Dew and Solar Water

Midsummer dew carried enormous importance in European folk belief.

Collected before sunrise on St. John’s morning, it was believed to absorb the strength of the solstice night itself.

People rolled in dew-covered grass for fertility and health. Women washed their faces in it for beauty and luck. Cloths were dragged across fields to gather dew for healing rituals.

Some traditions left herbs outdoors overnight so they absorbed both moonlight and the first dew of dawn before being dried for later ritual use.

This was part of an older seasonal worldview in which:

- water held memory,
- sunlight altered plants,
- dawn carried transitional force,
- and certain calendar nights intensified all three.

